Condition : 1 - The development hereby permitted shall begin not later than three years from the date of this decision.
Reason: In order to comply with Section 91 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990, as amended by Section 51 of the Planning and Compulsory Purchase Act 2004.
Condition : 2 - The development hereby permitted shall be carried out in accordance with the following approved plans and specifications: 
Biodiversity Net Gain Assessment (16099A-30-R02-02-F, March 2025), received 21/03/2025.
Drawings 24006-MII-ZZ-ZZ-DR-AR-0005(Rev.P4), 24006-MII-ZZ-ZZ-DR-AR-0010(Rev.P4) and 24006-MII-ZZ-ZZ-DR-AR-0100(Rev.P4), received 20/03/2025.
Transport Statement (24-398-20, Rev.04, dated 18/02/2025), received 18/02/2025.
Energy and Sustainability Statement (February 2025), received 06/02/2025.
Drawing 24006-MII-ZZ-ZZ-DR-AR-0400(Rev.P2), received 04/02/2025.
Drawing 24006-MII-ZZ-ZZ-DR-AR-0200(Rev.P2), received 24/01/2025.
Arboricultural Implications Report (Ref. SJA air 24427-01), BNG metric calculation, Design and Access Statement (Rev.P1, November 2024), Drainage Assessment Form, Drawings 90-122 ('Drainage Strategy', Rev.01), 24006-MII-ZZ-ZZ-DR-AR-0015(Rev.P1) and 24006-MII-ZZ-ZZ-DR-AR-0001(Rev.P1), Ecological Impact Assessment (16099A-30-R01-01-f, December 2024), Framework Construction Traffic Management Plan (23-398-20, Rev.01, 02/12/2024), Marketing Statement (November 2024) and Planning Statement (December 2024), all received 10/12/2024. 
Reason: In order to ensure the development is carried out in accordance with the planning permission.
Condition : 3 - Notwithstanding the provisions of the Town and Country Planning (General Permitted Development Order) 1995 (or any order revoking or re-enacting that order), no enlargement or alteration of the premises or erection of any additional structures/buildings/enclosures within the curtilage of the site shall be carried out, other than as shown in the approved drawings, and no additional floor space shall be formed within the buildings hereby permitted by means of internal horizontal division (e.g. new mezzanine levels) without prior written approval of the local planning authority. 
No cables, wires, aerials, pipework (except any rainwater downpipes as may be shown on the approved drawings), meter boxes or flues shall be fixed to any elevation facing a highway.
Reason:  To protect neighbours' living conditions and the character and appearance of the area and to prevent over-intensive use of the site.
Condition : 4 - No development above ground level shall take place until full details and samples of all materials to be used in the construction of the external surfaces of the development hereby permitted have been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority. Details must include a detailed schedule of materials, a photographic sample board and rendered drawings, elevations and sections at a sufficient scale (1:20 or 1:50) to illustrate how all external materials will appear together.
The samples/details shall include: 
(i)	Brick/stonework (including brick, stone, masonry, brick panels, feature brick panel, brick framing feature and mortar on-site sample panel, minimum one metre by one metre) including all mortar colours, joint type, brick bond;
(ii)	Cladding materials / render (including specifications where relevant);
(iii)	Tiles / roof covering; including parapet coping / capping materials, dormers and canopies;
(iv)	Window types; and sectional drawings of reveals / sills / head details 
(v)	Balcony details (including soffits, panels and frame);
(vi)	All privacy measures (including obscure glazing details, privacy screens etc.);
(vii)	Balustrading treatment and handrails to balconies and roof areas (including details / sections / materials);
(viii)	Any other materials/details / fittings to be used (including solar panels, extract vents, rainwater goods, boiler flues etc.), with sections and on-site samples where appropriate
(ix)	Balustrading treatment (including details / sections / materials); and
(x)	Any other materials / details / fittings to be used (including solar panels, extract vents, rainwater goods, boiler flues etc.), with sections and on-site samples where appropriate
The development shall then be carried out in accordance with the approved details and maintained as such thereafter.
Reason: In order to protect the appearance of the area.
Condition : 5 - (a) The development hereby permitted shall be implemented in accordance with the approved Energy Strategy.
(b) Prior to first occupation of any unit within the development hereby approved, evidence (e.g. photographs, installation contracts and As-Built certificates under the Standard Assessment Procedure/National Calculation Method) shall be submitted to the local planning authority and approved in writing to show that the development has been constructed in accordance with the approved Energy Strategy, and any subsequent approved revisions, and achieved a 73% reduction in emissions or greater.
Reason: In order to ensure that the development makes the fullest contribution to minimising carbon dioxide emissions.
Condition : 6 - (A) No development above ground level shall take place until details have been submitted to and approved by the local planning authority which demonstrate that:
(i)	At least three of the key elements of the building envelope (external walls, windows roof, upper floor slabs, internal walls, floor finishes/coverings) are to achieve a rating of A+ to D in the Building Research Establishment (BRE) The Green Guide of specification.
(ii)	At least 50% of timber and timber products are to be sourced from accredited Forest Stewardship Council (FSC) or Programme for the Endorsement of Forestry Certification (PEFC) scheme.
(iii)	No construction or insulation materials are to be used which would release toxins into the internal and external environment, including those that deplete stratospheric ozone.
(B) The development shall not be occupied until evidence (e.g. photographs and copies of installation contracts) has been submitted to the local planning authority to demonstrate that the development has been carried out in accordance with the approved details under Part A of this condition. The development shall be maintained in accordance with the approved details at all times thereafter.
Reason: In the interests of sustainable development. 
Condition : 7 - Prior to first occupation of the buildings hereby approved, the development shall have been constructed to achieve an internal water use of 105 litres/person/day or less.
Reason: In order to protect and conserve water supplies and resources.
Condition : 8 - No development shall take place until the applicant has entered into a binding arrangement with the Council to make an agreed contribution to the Council's Carbon Offset Fund, in accordance with the zero carbon strategy set out in the Energy Statement hereby approved to an amount that equates to the shortfall in required energy savings to meet the 'zero carbon' target. 
Reason: In order to ensure the development meets sustainability standards.
Condition : 9 - Prior to the occupation of the development, full details of the proposed heat pumps shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. These shall include:
�	An estimate of the heating and/or cooling energy (MWh/annum) the heat pumps would provide to the development and the percentage of contribution to the site's heat loads to demonstrate how the heat fraction from heat pump technologies has been maximised;
�	Details of the Seasonal Coefficient of Performance (SCOP) and/or Seasonal Energy Efficiency ratio (SEER) and how these have been calculated including the expected heat source and heat distribution temperatures (for space heat and hot water) and the distribution loss factor, which shall be calculated based on the above information;
�	Details of all screening and noise mitigation measures to demonstrate that all heat pumps would meet relevant noise limits and not cause harm to occupiers' or neighbouring living conditions.
The development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details.
Reason: To achieve appropriate sustainability standards.
Condition : 10 - A.	Prior to commencement of any above-ground development, details of the specifications (regarding power), number, appearance, location, orientation, total area and predicted carbon savings from the photovoltaic panels shall have been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority to show how the renewable energy carbon savings are to be achieved and maximised. The photovoltaic panels shall be installed in accordance with the approved details prior to the occupation of the relevant part of the development and retained and maintained as such unless otherwise agreed by the Local Planning Authority. 
B.	No solar panels shall be installed until a glint and glare assessment has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. No subsequent alterations to the approved scheme are to take place unless submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.
Reason: To achieve appropriate sustainability standards and to ensure the development does not endanger the safe movement of aircraft or the operation of Heathrow Airport. The airport requires a glint and glare assessment to be completed to determine the full impact on Air Traffic Control Tower and pilots approaching the airport.
Condition : 11 - All removal of trees, hedgerows, shrubs, scrub or tall herbaceous vegetation shall be undertaken between September and February inclusive. If this is not possible then a suitably qualified ecologist shall check the areas concerned immediately prior to the clearance works to ensure that no nesting or nest-building birds are present. If any nesting birds are present, then the vegetation shall not be removed until the fledglings have left the nest.
Reason: All wild birds, their nests and young are protected during the nesting period under The Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (as amended). In the interests of nature conservation and biodiversity.
Condition : 12 - No development shall take place until the following details have been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority:
(i)	A plan showing the position of each tree on the site and on land adjacent to the site (including street trees) that could influence or be affected by the development, indicating which trees are to be removed;
(ii)	A schedule in relation to each tree identified listing species, diameter and approximate height, and an assessment on the general state of health and stability of each tree, in accordance with British Standard 5837:2012 (or in an equivalent British Standard if replaced); and any proposed pruning, felling or other works;
(iii)	Details of any proposed alterations to existing ground levels, and of the position of any proposed excavation, that may affect the root protection area of retained trees;
(iv)	Details of the fencing to be installed for the protection of retained trees.
The development shall not be carried out otherwise than in accordance with the approved details, which shall be put into effect at the commencement of work on site and retained permanently for the duration of the development works.
Reason: In order to ensure a satisfactory appearance of the site and the area and to promote biodiversity. 
Condition : 13 - Notwithstanding any details included in the submitted plans, no development above ground level (except any demolition, site clearance, ground investigation and remediation work) shall take place until details of both hard and soft landscape works have been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority. These details shall include:
(i)	a statement setting out the design objectives and how these will be delivered; 
(ii)	existing and proposed finished levels or contours; 
(iii)	means of enclosure/boundary treatment(s) and retaining structures;
(iv)	vehicle parking layouts and markings; 
(v)	other vehicle and pedestrian access and circulation areas;
(vi)	hard surfacing materials; 
(vii)	minor artefacts and structures (e.g. furniture, refuse or other storage units, signs, lighting, CCTV etc.); 
(viii)	any children's play equipment and surfacing within the shared landscaped area;
(ix)	proposed and existing functional services above and below ground (e.g. drainage, power, communications cables, pipelines etc. indicating alignments, levels, access points, supports as relevant); 
(x)	details of all external lighting, including measures to switch off when not required and details of mitigation measures to avoid lightspill onto sensitive receptors (habitable rooms and any ecologically sensitive parts of the site);
(xi)	any renewable energy installations (including air source heat pump screening where required);
(xii)	details of tree planting, including quantity, size, species, and positions or density of all trees to be planted, alongside details of how they will be planted and protected and the proposed times of planting; 
(xiii)	planting plans, written specifications (including cultivation and other operations associated with plant and grass establishment) and schedules of plants, noting species, plant sizes and proposed numbers and densities where appropriate and including details of screen planting of an appropriate height along the fron
Condition : 14 - Prior to first use or occupation of the development, a plan indicating the heights (no higher than 0.6 metres within the pedestrian visibility splays along the front boundary), positions, design, materials and type of boundary treatment to be erected shall have been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority; the boundary treatment shall be erected as approved before the development is first brought into use and shall be retained as such thereafter. 
Reason: In order to protect neighbours' living conditions, ensure a satisfactory appearance of the site and area and minimise danger, obstruction and inconvenience to users of the highway and vehicular access.
Condition : 15 - No development shall take place until a Construction Logistics and Environmental Management Plan (CLEMP), drafted in accordance with current TfL guidance, has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The CLEMP shall include:
(i)	a site plan (showing the elements set out below);
(ii)	an identification of stages of works;
(iii)	confirmation that a pre-start record of site conditions on the adjoining public highway will be undertaken with Hounslow Highways and a commitment to repair any damage caused;
(iv)	provision for the parking of vehicles of site operatives and visitors;
(v)	provisions for loading, unloading and storage of plant and materials within the site;
(vi)	details of access to the site, including means to control and manage access and egress of vehicles to and from the site for the duration of construction including phasing arrangements;
(vii)	details of the proposed access road and pavements across the site, including at the junction with Staines Road; 
(viii)	details of vehicle routeing from the site to the wider strategic road network;
(ix)	the erection and maintenance of security hoarding including decorative displays and facilities for public viewing, where appropriate;
(x)	provision of wheel washing facilities at the site exit and a commitment to sweep adjacent roads when required and at the request of the Council;
(xi)	a scheme for recycling/disposing of waste resulting from demolition and construction works;
(xii)	measures to ensure the safety of all users of the public highway especially cyclists and pedestrians in the vicinity of the site and especially at the access;
(xiii)	commitment to liaise with other contractors in the vicinity of the site to maximise the potential for consolidation and to minimise traffic impacts;
(xiv)	avoidance of peak hours for deliveries and details of a booking system to avoid vehicles waiting on the public highway;
(xv)	all necessary traffic orders and other permission
Condition : 16 - No demolition or construction work shall take place on the site except between the hours of 8:00am to 6:00pm on Mondays to Friday and 8:00am to 1:00pm on Saturdays and none shall take place on Sundays and Public Holidays without the prior agreement of the Local Planning Authority. Additionally, HGV deliveries to site during the course of construction will be restricted to 9.30am and 3.00pm on Mondays to Friday, and 9.30am to 1.00pm on Saturdays, and none shall take place on Sundays and Public Holidays without the prior agreement of the Local Planning Authority.
Reason: To ensure that the proposed development does not prejudice the amenities of the locality and to prevent obstruction and inconvenience to users of the public highway.
Condition : 17 - Before the development hereby permitted is first occupied or brought into use, a Delivery and Servicing Plan (including details of vehicle access and egress arrangements and times that servicing shall take place) shall have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The details shall accord with current guidance such as that issued by TfL and include measures required to ensure sufficient arrangements (physical as well as managerial) for the servicing, including refuse collection, of all aspects of the development, the timing of hours for deliveries by motor vehicles and a timetable for implementation. The development shall not be carried out otherwise than in accordance with the approved details and shall be maintained for the lifetime of the development, unless the prior written approval of the Local Planning Authority is obtained to any variation.
Reason: In the interests of the safety of pedestrians and vehicles, to protect neighbours' living conditions and to support sustainable transport objectives.
Condition : 18 - Before the development hereby permitted is first occupied or brought into use, a Parking Management Plan shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The Plan shall include the following:
(i)	A finalised plan of the demarcated parking spaces with dimensions 2.4 x 4.8m; 
(ii)	details of parking allocations for residents of the approved development and how this will be operated, managed and enforced;
(iii)	details of measures proposed to restrict parking to four designated bays only and prohibit parking on the access road, grass verges, vehicular access points or anywhere else on the site beyond the specified bays;
(iv)	confirmation that passive provision for electrical vehicles will be laid out for all four parking spaces, with a commitment to convert passive EV bays to active when demand requires;
(v)	measures to ensure that all prospective residents are informed of the Parking Management Plan and that no dwelling is to be assigned more than one parking space.
The parking and circulation areas and access road shall thereafter be managed in compliance with the approved Parking Management Plan, unless the prior written approval of the local planning authority is obtained to secure any variation.
Reason: In order to promote sustainable modes of transport, to protect neighbours' living conditions and to ensure minimal disruption of traffic in the locality.
Condition : 19 - Either side of the vehicle access hereby approved, visibility splay areas (the depth measured from the back of the footway and the widths outwards from the edges of the access, with a splay of at least 2.4 metres x 2.4 metres) shall be provided before the enhanced access and parking area is brought into use. These areas shall be kept clear of any obstructions to visibility greater than 0.6 metres in height, including shrubs, planting, boundary walls, fences, gates, other means of enclosure or other structures or objects at all times.
Reason:  To ensure adequate visibility for drivers entering and leaving the site in the interests of pedestrian and vehicle safety.
Condition : 20 - Means of vehicle access to the permitted development shall be from Cranford Lane via the dedicated vehicular access front of the site only. Notwithstanding the provisions of the Town and Country Planning (General Permitted Development Order) 1995 (or any order revoking or re-enacting that order), no other means of access shall be formed to the site. 
Reason: In the interests of pedestrian and vehicle safety
Condition : 21 - Prior to the commencement of above ground works, the applicant shall have submitted and had approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority a Road Safety Audit (RSA) for the proposed access arrangements onto Cranford Lane. The RSA shall include an assessment of pedestrian and vehicular movements, as well as any mitigation measures necessary to address identified safety concerns. Any necessary changes identified in the RSA shall be implemented as part of the development and secured via an S278 Agreement.
Reason: To ensure highway safety is maintained and preserved.	
Condition : 22 - Prior to first use or occupation of the development, finalised details of the arrangements for the storing of waste and recycled materials (including details of how the placing of waste and recycled materials in a suitable location for collection would be undertaken and managed and demonstrating compliance with the Council's Recycling and Refuse Guidelines SPD) shall have been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority. The development shall not be carried out otherwise than in accordance with the approved details.
All refuse and recycling bins and delivery carts in association with the approved development are to be stored within the approved facilities at all times and only brought out when deliveries are being made or refuse collected.
Reason: In order to ensure adequate provision for waste and recycling.
Condition : 23 - Prior to first use or occupation of the development full details (including manufacturers' specifications) of secure covered cycle parking facilities that accord with the West London Cycle Parking Guidance for the occupants of, and visitors to, the development shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The approved facilities shall be fully implemented and made available for use before the development is first occupied or brought into use, The approved facilities shall be thereafter retained for use at all times without obstruction.
Reason: In order to support sustainable transport objectives.
Condition : 24 - Prior to commencement of the development hereby approved:
Following the completion of the Phase I desk study report, if intrusive investigations or gas monitoring is recommended, a Phase II site investigation must be undertaken. 
No development other than necessary works to enable intrusive investigations shall take place until a Phase II site investigation report, prepared by a suitably qualified, experienced or supervised person, has been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority. 
This report shall identify the areas and sources of land contamination that exist on the site and identify the scope of site remediation measures necessary before the development commences.
The investigation shall be carried out by a competent person(s), based on the initial Conceptual Site Model (CSM) and on-site observations, to identify the extent and nature of contaminants. The initial CSM shall be updated accordingly following a tiered risk assessment based on the findings of the investigation, and where applicable, the report shall include proposals to deal with the identified contamination on site. 
Reason: Contamination is known or suspected on the site due to a former land use. It is therefore necessary to ensure that the development can be implemented and occupied with adequate regard for public and environmental safety.
Supporting Notes:
(i)	The report shall include details of such sampling of soil, soil vapour, ground gas, leachate, surface water and/or groundwater at such locations and depths as are considered to characterise the site conditions based on the initial Conceptual Site Model (CSM) and on-site observations during investigation work. 
(ii)	The investigation and the report must adhere to current UK guidance and best practice.
(iii)	Further investigation shall be carried out at such locations and at such depths as the local planning authority may stipulate if this report is found to be insufficient or where it is deemed necessary
Condition : 25 - Prior to commencement of the development hereby approved:
If a scheme for remediation is recommended in the Phase II site investigation for the site, no development shall take place until a remediation method statement prepared by a suitably qualified, experienced or supervised person to specify the works necessary to render the site suitable for its proposed end use, has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. 
Reason: Contamination is known or suspected on the site due to a former land use. It is therefore necessary to ensure that the development can be implemented and occupied with adequate regard for public and environmental safety.
Supporting Notes:
(i)	The remediation method statement shall provide suitable details of how the risks of each pollutant linkages, as identified in the updated Conceptual Site Model, will be mitigated.
(ii)	The report shall account for any comments made by the Local Planning Authority. 
(iii)	Remediation work shall be carried out in accordance with the approved remediation method statement for verification and validation before the development is first brought into use.
(iv)	The Council requests that remediation method statement or site plans be sent electronically to landquality@hounslow.gov.uk as well as being submitted to the Local Planning Authority for approval.
Condition : 26 - During the development:
The Local Planning Authority shall be notified immediately if any land contamination not previously identified is encountered during development. A competent person shall assess the contamination, where necessary, including soil and groundwater sampling and testing before any further part of the development that may be affected by the additional contamination that has been discovered continues. 
A revised remediation method statement, prepared by a suitably qualified, experienced or supervised person, shall be submitted in writing to the Local Planning Authority for approval within one month of the discovery of such contamination. 
Reason: Contamination is known or suspected on the site due to a former land use. It is therefore necessary to ensure that the development can be implemented and occupied with adequate regard for public and environmental safety.
Supporting notes:
(i)	Further remediation work to remove or manage additional contamination shall be carried out in accordance with the approved revised remediation method statement for verification and validation before the development is first brought into use. 
(ii)	In some instances, the Local Planning Authority may require work on site to be ceased whilst the nature of additional contamination is investigated fully.
(iii)	The Council requests that the revised remediation method statement or any site photos be sent electronically to landquality@hounslow.gov.uk as well as being submitted to the Local Planning Authority for approval.
Condition : 27 - Before the development is first brought into use:
The agreed scheme for remediation, including any amendments, shall be fully implemented. A verification report produced upon completion of the remediation by a suitably qualified, experienced or supervised person shall be submitted in writing to the Local Planning Authority for approval, before the development is first brought into use or in accordance with a programme approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. 
Reason: Contamination is known or suspected on the site due to a former land use. It is therefore necessary to ensure that the development can be implemented and occupied with adequate regard for public and environmental safety.
Supporting notes:
(i)	The verification (closure) report shall revisit the conceptual site model and provide evidence that each aspect of the remediation plan has been implemented correctly and successfully in accordance with current UK guidance and best practice. Where applicable, the report shall describe how any additional/unexpected contamination encountered during development has been managed in line with the revised remediation method statement. 
(ii)	This report shall demonstrate that the development is suitable for its proposed use in terms of land quality.
(iii)	The Council requests that the verification report or site photos be sent electronically to landquality@hounslow.gov.uk as well as being submitted to the Local Planning Authority for approval.
Condition : 28 - If long term monitoring and maintenance is required following successful completion of approved remedial measures, reports which demonstrate the effectiveness of the monitoring and maintenance shall be prepared by a suitably qualified, experienced or supervised person and submitted to the Local Planning Authority according to an agreed timescale as shall first have been approved under other conditions set out in this planning approval decision notice. 
This shall be conducted in accordance with current UK guidance and best practice. 
Reason: In order to ensure that risks from land contamination to the future users of the land and neighbouring land are minimised, together with those to controlled waters, properties and ecological systems.
Condition : 29 - Prior to commencement of groundworks (excluding site investigations and demolition), the applicant shall have submitted to the local planning authority and had approved in writing a final detailed drainage design including drawings, supporting calculations and an updated Drainage Assessment Form, aligned with the drainage submissions hereby approved. The applicant should incorporate green infrastructure into the design and should confirm whether infiltration is feasible by providing the results of infiltration testing. A detailed management plan confirming routine maintenance tasks for all drainage components (including frequencies for each drainage component and who will own the tasks) shall also be submitted to demonstrate how the drainage system is to be maintained for the lifetime of the development. The development shall be carried out in strict compliance with the approved details.
Reason: To prevent the risk of flooding to and from the site.
Condition : 30 - No building hereby permitted shall be occupied until evidence (including photographs and installation contracts along with a written confirmation) has been submitted to the local planning authority and approved in writing to demonstrate that the sustainable drainage scheme for the site has been completed in accordance with the submitted details. The sustainable drainage scheme shall be managed and maintained thereafter in accordance with the agreed management and maintenance plan for all of the proposed drainage components. The name of the maintenance owner should be confirmed.
Reason: To prevent the risk of flooding to and from the site.
Condition : 31 - (a)	The development shall achieve 'Secured by Design' accreditation awarded by the Design-Out Crime Officer from the Metropolitan Police Service on behalf of the Association of Chief Police Officers (ACPO).
(b)	Prior to first use, accreditation will be evidenced as achieved and evidence of such accreditation will need to be submitted and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.
Reason: To tackle crime and disorder and to ensure that the development provides a safe and secure environment.
